      <ClinicalAssertion ID="14500573" SubmissionDate="2026-04-23" ContributesToAggregateClassification="false" DateLastUpdated="2026-05-16" DateCreated="2026-05-16">
        <ClinVarSubmissionID localKey="NM_005957.5:c.665C&gt;T|OMIM:236250" submittedAssembly="GRCh38"/>
        <ClinVarAccession Accession="SCV007593630" DateUpdated="2026-05-16" DateCreated="2026-05-16" Type="SCV" Version="1" SubmitterName="Variantyx, Inc." OrgID="506526" OrganizationCategory="laboratory"/>
        <RecordStatus>current</RecordStatus>
        <Classification DateLastEvaluated="2025-06-20">
          <ReviewStatus>criteria provided, single submitter</ReviewStatus>
          <GermlineClassification>Likely Pathogenic</GermlineClassification>
          <Citation>
            <ID Source="PubMed">25736335</ID>
          </Citation>
          <Citation>
            <ID Source="PubMed">26872964</ID>
          </Citation>
          <Citation>
            <ID Source="PubMed">10679944</ID>
          </Citation>
          <Citation>
            <ID Source="PubMed">12673793</ID>
          </Citation>
          <Citation>
            <ID Source="PubMed">25162892</ID>
          </Citation>
          <Citation>
            <ID Source="PubMed">25856670</ID>
          </Citation>
          <Comment Type="public">This is a nonsynonymous variant in the MTHFR gene (OMIM: 607093). Pathogenic variants in this gene have been associated with autosomal recessive homocystinuria due to methylenetetrahydrofolate reductase (MTHFR) deficiency. Homozygosity of this variant may result in mild-to-moderate hyperhomocysteinemia, which has been associated with an increased risk of venous thrombosis, ischemic stroke, coronary heart disease, and obstetrical complications (PMID: 18990318, 9869152, 9878639, 12196644). A study suggests that lifelong moderate homocysteine elevation may have little to no effect on the risk of coronary heart disease (PMID 22363213). Functional studies have shown that this variant alters MTHFR protein function (PMID: 27743313) (PS3) and multiple computational algorithms predict a deleterious effect for this variant (REVEL score: 0.842) (PP3_Moderate). This variant has a 47.7744% maximum allele frequency in control populations (gnomAD, https://gnomad.broadinstitute.org/) (BS1). The MTHFR c.665C&gt;T; p.Ala222Val variant (rs1801133), also known as C677T or the "thermolabile" variant, is listed in the ClinVar database (Variation ID: 3520), it was reviewed by expert panel (3 stars in clinVar) for drug response. This variant has been found to influence methotrexate metabolism in individuals treated for autoimmune disease or hematological malignancies, with both heterozygous and homozygous individuals having an increased risk of adverse drug reaction (https://www.pharmgkb.org/variant/PA16615364). Based on the current evidence, this variant is classified as likely pathogenic.</Comment>
        </Classification>
